# Add the Wake-Registry Late-Fire Reconciler

## Step

New Inngest function in `packages/system-bus`: every ~5 minutes and on startup, read pending registry entries, re-emit `pane.schedule.due` with the existing `scheduleId` for entries past due (grace window; `late: true` beyond 5 minutes), idempotent by `scheduleId`, delete only after confirmed delivery; plus `onFailure` on `pane/schedule` as observability only. Design per Clodpool's diagnosis: `pane-schedule.ts:12-64` has no onFailure and deletes only on success; `sleep.ts:306-320` shows everything as pending. Evidence: schedule `de16dde1` failed terminally 2026-07-19T21:34Z and sits pending forever. Resolved when an overdue entry (de16dde1 is the live test case) gets re-emitted as a late fire and drains. In flight via the `reboot-automation-fixes` workflow (run `wf_a79ef492-610`), steering session 2026-07-20.

## Result (2026-07-20)

Implemented as `pane/schedule.reconcile` (cron */5 + startup + on-demand event), committed `d1a37e89` with surgical staging around another session's in-flight consumer wiring. Deployment tripped the known dead-binding failure mode: the worker's self-registration PUT fired into the purge-window Inngest outage and was lost; re-registered manually (PUT /api/inngest, `modified:true`). Proven live on the charter's own test case: de16dde1 (orphaned 18h) swept at 15:30:42Z, re-emitted late, registry drained to exactly the two healthy chain successors. Minor follow-ups from verify: cancelled-schedule resurrection edge (CLI crash between cancel-event and hdel), unbounded failures/dead hashes — recorded in Latent.
